{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a5678634-15f6-479e-a40e-9c733a968fcc","content":"## What's happening\n\n**.NET 11 raised the minimum x86-64 CPU baseline**, likely from **x86-64-v2** to **x86-64-v3**. Your 2012-era hardware predates the required instruction sets.\n\n### x86-64 microarchitecture levels\n\n| Level | Key additions | Earliest Intel | Year |\n|-------|--------------|----------------|------|\n| v1 | SSE, SSE2 (original x86-64) | Prescott | 2004 |\n| v2 | SSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT | Nehalem | 2008 |\n| **v3** | **AVX2, BMI1, BMI2, FMA, F16C** | **Haswell** | **2013** |\n| v4 | AVX-512 | Skylake-X | 2017 |\n\nYour 2012 nodes are likely **Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge** — they support up to v2 (SSE4.2, AVX1) but **lack AVX2, BMI, and FMA** required by v3.\n\n### Why your other platforms are fine\n\n- **Windows ARM64 (SQ1):** ARM has a separate baseline; the Armv8.0 instructions the SQ1 supports are sufficient.\n- **Raspberry Pi 4 (Cortex-A72):** Also Armv8.0 — meets .NET's ARM64 baseline.\n\n### Your options\n\n1. **Replace the 2012 hardware** with Haswell-era (2013+) or newer CPUs — the real fix.\n2. **Stay on .NET 10 (LTS)** for those specific nodes until the hardware is retired.\n3. **Check for a compat switch** — some .NET releases have offered a `DOTNET_EnableSSE3_4=0`-style fallback or a v2-baseline build, but this is not guaranteed and may hurt performance. Check the .NET 11 release notes.\n\nYou can verify what a node supports by running:\n\n```bash\n# On the failing Linux node:\nlscpu | grep -i flags | tr ' ' '\\n' | grep -iE 'avx2|bmi|fma'\n```\n\nIf that returns empty, the CPU doesn't meet v3 — confirming the diagnosis.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"919c9a38-55fa-425f-93eb-def47d50660e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a known change in the .NET ecosystem that I can explain from my knowledge.\n\nStarting with .NET 9, there were discussions about raising the x86-64 baseline. Let me think about what happened:\n\n- .NET 8 and earlier targeted the original x86-64 baseline (x86-64-v1), which is compatible with all x86-64 CPUs.\n- Starting with .NET 9 or later versions, Microsoft raised the minimum CPU baseline for x86-64 to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT instructions.\n\n\n- Since the user is upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11, and .NET 10 already had the v2 baseline, I should check whether .NET 11 raised the requirements even further.\n\nLet me map out the microarchitecture levels to understand what each one includes: v1 is the original baseline with just SSE and SSE2, v2 adds the vector extensions like SSE3 through SSE4.2, v3 brings in AVX and AVX2 along with BMI and FMA instructions, and v4 goes even further.\n\nNow I'm checking the hardware timeline—Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge from 2011-2012 support AVX but crucially lack AVX2, BMI1, BMI2, and FMA, which only arrived with Haswell in 2013. So if .NET 11 bumped the baseline to v3, it would break compatibility with that entire generation of processors. I need to verify what actually shipped in .NET 9 versus what was just discussed. The error indicates the CPU lacks instruction sets that .NET 11 requires at minimum—likely AVX2 and related instructions from x86-64-v3 that Sandy Bridge doesn't support. I should clarify the actual .NET timeline and explain their options across the different platforms they mentioned, including the ARM64 and Raspberry Pi considerations. So if .NET 11 raised the baseline to x86-64-v3, which requires AVX2, BMI, and FMA instructions that Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge CPUs from 2012 don't support, that would explain why the user's older hardware broke. The ARM-based platforms wouldn't be affected since they have their own separate instruction set requirements. I should present this as the most likely explanation while being clear about the uncertainty around .NET 11's actual release status and specific changes.","outputTokens":2120,"requestId":"B00E:867F7:F778EF:11BD08A:69F2B369"},"id":"beafd158-8aec-4749-97b3-9411756b09e7","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:42:45.153Z","parentId":"2bea7e33-06f8-4f07-905d-62ba4928a69c"}
